In the parallelogram, suppose that $d$ is opposite $a.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (4,3);
B = (1,-2);
C = (8,-5);
D = B + C - A;

draw(A--B--D--C--cycle);
draw(A--D,dashed);
draw(B--C,dashed);

dot("$a$", A, N);
dot("$b$", B, W);
dot("$c$", C, E);
dot("$d$", D, S);
dot((A + D)/2);
[/asy]

Recall that in any parallelogram, the midpoints of the diagonals coincide.  Hence,
\[\frac{a + d}{2} = \frac{b + c}{2},\]which leads to $d = b + c - a.$

The complex number $d$ can also be opposite $b$ or $c,$ which leads to the possible values $d = a + c - b$ and $d = a + b - c.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (4,3);
B = (1,-2);
C = (8,-5);

draw((B + C - A)--(A + C - B)--(A + B - C)--cycle,dashed);
draw(A--B--C--cycle,dashed);

dot("$a$", A, N);
dot("$b$", B, W);
dot("$c$", C, E);

dot("$b + c - a$", B + C - A, S);
dot("$a + c - b$", A + C - B, E);
dot("$a + b - c$", A + B - C, NW);
[/asy]

Thus, the possible values of $d$ are
\begin{align*}
b + c - a &= (1 - 2i) + (8 - 5i) - (4 + 3i) = \boxed{5 - 10i}, \\
a + c - b &= (4 + 3i) + (8 - 5i) - (1 - 2i) = \boxed{11}, \\
a + b - c &= (4 + 3i) + (1 - 2i) - (8 - 5i) = \boxed{-3 + 6i}.
\end{align*}

Let $a = \angle DAB = \frac{1}{2} \angle CAD.$  Since $\frac{AC}{AD} = \frac{2}{3},$ without loss of generality, we can assume $AC = 2$ and $AD = 3.$  Then by Pythagoras on right triangle $ACD,$ $CD = \sqrt{5}.$

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

real u = 5/9;
pair A, B, C, D, E;

A = (0,0);
C = (2*u,0);
D = (2*u,sqrt(5)*u);
E = interp(C,D,2/5);
B = extension(A, reflect(A,D)*(E), C, D);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, dir(0));
label("$2$", (A + C)/2, S);
label("$3$", (A + D)/2, NW);
label("$\sqrt{5}$", (C + D)/2, dir(0));
[/asy]

From right triangle $ACD,$ $\cos 2a = \frac{2}{3}.$  Then from the half-angle formula,
\begin{align*}
\sin a &= \sqrt{\frac{1 - \cos 2a}{2}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}, \\
\cos a &= \sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos 2a}{2}} = \sqrt{\frac{5}{6}}.
\end{align*}By the Law of Sines on triangle $ABD,$
\[\frac{BD}{\sin a} = \frac{3}{\sin (90^\circ - 3a)},\]so
\[BD = \frac{3 \sin a}{\cos 3a} = \frac{3 \sin a}{4 \cos^3 a - 3 \cos a} = \frac{3 \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}}{\frac{4 \cdot 5 \cdot \sqrt{5}}{6 \sqrt{6}} - \frac{3 \sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{6}}} = \frac{9}{\sqrt{5}}.\]Hence,
\[\frac{CD}{BD} = \frac{\sqrt{5}}{9/\sqrt{5}} = \boxed{\frac{5}{9}}.\]

We will calculate the area of the hexagon in two different ways.  Let the interior point in the figure be called $P$, and let $s$ be the side length of the hexagon. The areas of the triangles $APB$, $BPC$, $CPD$, $DPE$, $EPF$, and $FPA$ are $\frac{1}{2}(s)(4)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(6)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(9)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(10)$, $\frac{1}{2}(s)(8)$, and $\frac{1}{2}(s)(5)$, respectively.  Also, the area of a regular hexagon with side length $s$ is $3s^2\sqrt{3}/2$.  Setting the sum of the triangles' areas equal to $3s^2\sqrt{3}/2$ gives \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2}s(4 + 6 + 9 + 10 + 8 + 5)&=\frac{3s^2\sqrt{3}}{2} \implies \\
21s&=\frac{3s^2\sqrt{3}}{2} \implies \\
14s &= s^2\sqrt{3} \implies \\
s=0 \quad \text{or} \quad s &= \frac{14}{\sqrt{3}} \\
&= \frac{14}{\sqrt{3}}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3}}=\boxed{\frac{14\sqrt{3}}{3}} \text{ cm}.
\end{align*}[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, P, U, V, W, X, Y, Z;

A = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(60);
B = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(120);
C = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(180);
D = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(240);
E = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(300);
F = 14*sqrt(3)/3*dir(360);
P = extension(A + (0,-4), B + (0,-4), A + 5*dir(210), F + 5*dir(210));

U = (P + reflect(A,B)*(P))/2;
V = (P + reflect(B,C)*(P))/2;
W = (P + reflect(C,D)*(P))/2;
X = (P + reflect(D,E)*(P))/2;
Y = (P + reflect(E,F)*(P))/2;
Z = (P + reflect(F,A)*(P))/2;

draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--cycle);
draw(U--X,dotted);
draw(V--Y,dotted);
draw(W--Z,dotted);
draw(A--P);
draw(B--P);
draw(C--P);
draw(D--P);
draw(E--P);
draw(F--P);

label("$A$", A, dir(60));
label("$B$", B, dir(120));
label("$C$", C, dir(180));
label("$D$", D, dir(240));
label("$E$", E, dir(300));
label("$F$", F, dir(360));
label("$P$", P, SW, UnFill);
label("$4$", (P + U)/2, dir(180));
label("$6$", (P + V)/2, SW);
label("$9$", (P + W)/2, SE);
label("$10$", (P + X)/2, dir(180));
label("$8$", (P + Y)/2, SW);
label("$5$", (P + Z)/2, SE);
[/asy]

