draw(Circle((4,0),1));
draw(Circle((-4,0),1));
draw(Circle((4/sqrt(15),1),16/sqrt(15)),red);
draw((-6,0)--(6,0));
draw((0,-6)--(0,6));

dot("$(0,5)$", (0,5), NW);
dot((4,0));
dot((-4,0));
[/asy]

By symmetry, there is only one circle that is internally tangent to the circle centered at $(-4,0)$ and externally tangent to the circle centered at $(4,0),$ giving us a total of $\boxed{4}$ circles.

Since $\cot^{-1} \left( \frac{1}{x} \right) = \tan^{-1} x$ for all $x,$ we can write
\[\sin \left( 2 \tan^{-1} x \right) = \frac{1}{3}.\]Let $\theta = \tan^{-1} x,$ so $x = \tan \theta.$  Also, $\sin 2 \theta = \frac{1}{3},$ so
\[2 \sin \theta \cos \theta = \frac{1}{3}.\]Construct a right triangle with legs 1 and $x.$  Then the angle opposite the side length $x$ be $\theta.$

